\title{Quantum Information Gravity: Experimental Testability and Falsifiability}
\author{AXVIAM Research Group}
\date{}
\begin{document}
\maketitle
\begin{abstract}
This document formalizes the experimental testability and falsifiability criteria for Quantum Information Gravity (QIG). We identify key predictions, propose empirical tests, and outline the conditions under which QIG can be confirmed or refuted.
\end{abstract}
\section{Introduction}
Quantum Information Gravity (QIG) posits that gravity and spacetime geometry emerge from quantum information principles. For QIG to be a valid physical theory, it must make falsifiable predictions that distinguish it from general relativity (GR) and dark matter paradigms. Here, we outline the main avenues for experimental verification.
\section{Axiomatically-Derived Predictions}
The QIG formalism yields the following testable predictions:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Galactic Rotation Curves:} QIG predicts flat galactic rotation curves without invoking dark matter, with velocity profiles determined by the information density gradient:
  \[
  v^2(r) = r \cdot \alpha \left| \frac{1}{\Omega(r)} \frac{d\Omega}{dr} \right|
  \]
  where $\Omega(r)$ is the information density profile.
  \item \textbf{Lensing Profiles:} Gravitational lensing is determined by the entropy-modulated metric:
  \[
  \tilde{g}_{\mu\nu} = f(S) g_{\mu\nu}
  \]
  yielding lensing angles that can be compared to those predicted by GR with dark matter.
  \item \textbf{Black Hole Thermodynamics:} QIG modifies the Bekenstein-Hawking entropy-area law via information-theoretic corrections, potentially affecting Hawking radiation spectra.
  \item \textbf{Cosmic Expansion:} The Friedmann equation is modified to include entropy-dependent terms, predicting a specific acceleration history as a function of cosmic entropy.
\end{enumerate}
\section{Empirical Tests}
\subsection*{1. Rotation Curve Fitting Without Dark Matter}
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Data:} High-precision rotation curves from SPARC and other galaxy surveys.
  \item \textbf{Test:} Fit observed velocity profiles using the QIG formula for $v(r)$, using only luminous matter distributions to compute $\Omega(r)$.
  \item \textbf{Falsifiability:} If QIG cannot fit observed curves without dark matter, the theory is falsified.
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{2. Gravitational Lensing Profiles}
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Data:} Strong and weak lensing maps of galaxies and clusters.
  \item \textbf{Test:} Compute lensing angles using the QIG-modified metric and compare to observations.
  \item \textbf{Falsifiability:} Systematic discrepancies between QIG predictions and lensing data would falsify the theory.
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{3. Black Hole Entropy and Radiation}
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Data:} Observations of black hole thermodynamics (e.g., event horizon telescope, Hawking radiation signatures).
  \item \textbf{Test:} Search for deviations from the standard entropy-area law or radiation spectrum predicted by QIG corrections.
  \item \textbf{Falsifiability:} Absence of predicted deviations or presence of unpredicted phenomena would challenge QIG.
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{4. Cosmic Expansion History}
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Data:} Supernovae Ia, baryon acoustic oscillations, CMB observations.
  \item \textbf{Test:} Fit expansion history using the QIG-modified Friedmann equation and compare to $\Lambda$CDM fits.
  \item \textbf{Falsifiability:} Inability to match observed expansion rates would falsify the theory.
\end{itemize}
\section{Distinctive Signatures}
QIG predicts several distinctive signatures that can be sought empirically:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Absence of Dark Matter in Dwarf Galaxies:} QIG may predict different velocity profiles for low surface brightness and dwarf galaxies, providing a sharp test.
  \item \textbf{Entropy-Dependent Redshift Drift:} The entropy-modulated metric may induce a small, measurable drift in cosmological redshift over time.
  \item \textbf{Information-Induced Decoherence:} QIG suggests a link between cosmic entropy growth and quantum-to-classical transition rates, potentially observable in cosmological quantum systems.
\end{itemize}
\section{Experimental Falsifiability Criteria}
QIG is falsifiable if any of the following are observed:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Failure to fit galactic rotation curves or lensing without dark matter.
  \item No evidence for entropy corrections in black hole thermodynamics.
  \item Inability to account for cosmic acceleration history.
  \item Empirical confirmation of dark matter particles or fields inconsistent with QIG.
\end{enumerate}
\section{Conclusion}
QIG is a predictive and falsifiable theory. Its central claims---gravity and curvature as emergent from quantum information---can be tested against multiple lines of astrophysical and cosmological data. Ongoing and future observations (e.g., JWST, SKA, LISA) will provide decisive tests for the QIG framework.
\end{document}

