\title{Quantum Information Gravity: Unified Derivation}
\author{Christopher Smolen (aka Topher Booth)}
\date{\today}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\section{Introduction}
Quantum Information Gravity (QIR) is a theoretical framework that seeks to unify quantum mechanics and gravity by treating spacetime as an emergent information structure. Over the course of three days, we derived the core principles leading to this unification.

\section{Day 1: Establishing the Mathematical Foundations}
Day 1 focused on defining the information-based metric structure of spacetime, laying the groundwork for an entropic approach to gravity. We examined the implications of treating information as a conserved quantity in a dynamical geometric space.

\section{Day 2: Resolving Gravitational and Entropic Conflicts}
On Day 2, we tackled the apparent contradictions between quantum mechanics and classical gravity. Through a revised entropic formulation and the introduction of an information gradient, we reconciled the force laws governing both realms.

\section{Day 3: Unified Derivation and Empirical Predictions}
The third day was devoted to synthesizing the mathematical and conceptual insights into a unified formalism. We derived the following core equations:
\begin{align*}
S &= k \ln \Omega \\
\Phi(x) &= \alpha \ln \Omega(x) \\
F(x) &= -\nabla \Phi(x) = -\alpha \frac{\nabla \Omega(x)}{\Omega(x)}
\end{align*}
where $S$ is entropy, $\Omega$ is information density, $\Phi$ is the information potential, and $\alpha, k$ are constants.

We showed that the emergent force law reproduces gravitational phenomena without the need for dark matter:
\[
v^2(r) = r \cdot \alpha \left| \frac{1}{\Omega(r)} \frac{d\Omega}{dr} \right|
\]

We also demonstrated that the entropy-modulated metric yields empirical predictions for lensing and cosmic expansion:
\[
\tilde{g}_{\mu\nu} = f(S) g_{\mu\nu}
\]

\section{Conclusion}
The three-day derivation of Quantum Information Gravity provides a unified mathematical and conceptual foundation for the emergence of gravity from quantum information. This approach offers falsifiable predictions for rotation curves, lensing, and cosmic expansion, and suggests a path toward reconciling quantum mechanics and general relativity.

\end{document}

