\begin{document}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
This document presents a formal proof of the Quantum Information Reality (QIR) framework using tensor network representations. We show that gravity, curvature, and classical geometry emerge from the entanglement structure and information flow in quantum tensor networks, providing a geometric foundation for QIR.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Tensor networks are graphical representations of quantum many-body states, encoding entanglement and information structure. In QIR, spacetime geometry and gravity are emergent phenomena arising from the connectivity and entropic scaling of the underlying tensor network.

\section{Tensor Networks and Entanglement Geometry}

A tensor network is a collection of tensors (nodes) connected by edges (indices), representing quantum degrees of freedom and their correlations.

Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a tensor network state on Hilbert space $\mathcal{H}$. The entanglement entropy $S_A$ of a region $A$ is given by the minimal cut through the network separating $A$ from its complement $\bar{A}$:
\[
S_A = \min_{\text{cut}} \#(\text{edges}) \cdot s_0,
\]
where $s_0$ is the entropy per edge (e.g., $\ln d$ for qudit bond dimension $d$).

This reproduces the Ryu-Takayanagi formula in AdS/CFT:
\[
S_A = \frac{\text{Area}(\gamma_A)}{4G_N},
\]
where $\gamma_A$ is the minimal surface homologous to $A$.

\section{Emergent Geometry from Network Structure}

The connectivity of the tensor network defines an emergent geometry:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Distances correspond to minimal path lengths (number of edges).
  \item Curvature arises from the pattern of connections and entanglement scaling.
  \item The information metric $g_{\mu\nu}$ is induced by the Fisher information or quantum geometric tensor on the network.
\end{itemize}

\section{Gravity as Entanglement Force}

Following QIR, the information potential at a node $x$ is given by:
\[
